{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"text_start","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"15, 2025 deadline. The AAR prompt shows that the council members must evaluate whether Iran and the United States had agreed to a permanent peace deal by that date, based on preponderance of evidence.\n\nThe \"Record\" section describes the evidence admitted into the case. There are plaintiff exhibits (PX-Rules, PX-1, PX-2, PX-3, PX-4) and defendant exhibits (D-Rules, PX-1, PX-2, PX-3, PX-4, D-1, D-2), which are mostly duplicates of the same evidence but with separate labels. Looking at the key pieces of evidence:\n\n- PX-1 (White House June 17, 2025 statement): States \"You can't have peace if Iran has a nuclear weapon\" but does not say there's a permanent peace deal in place.\n- PX-2 (White House fact sheet Feb 2026): Says \"In June, after Iran refused to reach a deal with the United States, President Trump authorized Operation Midnight Hammer which obliterated Iran's nuclear facilities...\"\n- PX-3 (Reuters report June 15, 2025): Reports that U.S.-Iran nuclear talks scheduled for June 15 were cancelled.\n- PX-4 (Iran UN Vienna mission statement June 23, 2025): Describes U.S. attacks on Iranian nuclear facilities on June 22, 2025 as aggression and reaffirms Iran's right to self-defense.\n- D-1: Secretary Rubio's June 12, 2025 statement on Israel's unilateral action against Iran and US force protection.\n- D-2: Times of Oman report describing Iran's withdrawal from June 15 talks.\n\nThe Rules (both plaintiff and defendant) state that a permanent peace deal must \"explicitly indicate that military hostilities between the United States and Iran have ended or will permanently cease, or uses equivalent language clearly signaling a lasting end to military hostilities.\" The rules also specify that only either a signed agreement between governments or clear public confirmation from both governments counts as proof.\n\nNone of the evidence shows:\n- A signed agreement between Iran and the United States on June 15, 2025\n- Any matching public confirmation from both governments about a permanent end to hostilities\n- Any language indicating a \"permanent end to military hostilities\" - instead, the evidence shows:\n  * Cancellation of talks\n  * \"Refused to reach a deal\" language\n  * Military strikes against Iran's nuclear facilities (June 22)\n  * Statements about preventing Iran from having a nuclear weapon (not about peace)\n  * Statements about defending national interests\n\nBoth plaintiff and defendant arguments conclude that the evidence does not demonstrate the proposition. The plaintiff admits the \"admitted evidence I was able to find is materially adverse\", and the defendant states \"the admitted record now defeats the proposition.\"\n\nThe evidence clearly shows that there was no permanent peace deal by June 15, 2025 - in fact, the evidence shows military conflict continued afterward (U.S. attacks on June 22), and talks were cancelled/suspended before the deadline (on June 15).\n\nAs the council member, I should vote \"not_demonstrated\" because the record does not support that a permanent peace deal was reached by the deadline. My rationale should be concise, as instructed: no more than three sentences.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"My"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782836950610,"responseId":"gen-1782836950-UPPRN85Elq4NQjJO021m","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"15, 2025 deadline. The AAR prompt shows that the council members must evaluate whether Iran and the United States had agreed to a permanent p